{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_fleur_ver01/data/sn83035189/00516993741/1930112001/0424.xml":{"full_text":"ABERDEEN TOWN\nBE!NG REVAMPED\nBuilding of New Bridge\nof Great Benefit To\nViHage.\nGeorgetown News-Democrat:\u2014 Re\nvamping of Aberdeen has started with\nwork upon the bridge pier on the\nOhio side of the river for the bridge\nthat wiH span it, and the most ardent\ncitizens thereof hoid prediction for\nthe town that are inspiring. \"With\nin two years you are going to see\nAberdeen a town of no mean pro\nportions,\" they say, \"and one which\nwe propose to see modem in every\nfeature.\"\nAberdeen was not atways sucn as\nit is today. There are structures\nthere which indicate what the ideas\nof the men who conducted affairs\nyears ago thought of the viHage's\nfuture. There is a three-story hotel\nbuilding, nothing equalling it yet in\nBrown county. Along that river front\nthere was once a solid row of sub\nstantia! residences, only a few there\nnow, all of which have been carried\naway by Ohio river floods.\nBut that is all forgotten now. The\nbridge is first and with its completion\ncomes re-arrangement of streets, and\nthen Aberdeen becomes one vast area\nfor home building, the northern out\nlet for a great southern gateway of\na great northern trafHc.\nWorkmen are now engaged upon all\nthree abuttments for this river span.\nA great towering barge is in the river\nand at all points huge derricks are\nswinging away, and three shifts of\nworkmen are being brought into clock\nwork. The object for this hustling is\nthat the three piers can be builded\nabove high water in the river and the\nconstruction can carry on to comple\ntion without interference. Every in\ndication is there that this will prevail.\nBut Aberdeen's revamping is not to\nbe in the bridge alone. Its rear\nrangement or location of thorough\nfares that will feed the structure its\ntrafHc. Maysville has nothing so idea!\nin the way of arteries from the south\nto the bridge. Surveys have been\nmade for Ohio and the drawings are\nimpressive.\nFrom the north comes Zane Trace,\nhistorically known, and already so be\nsought with trafHc that the section\nsouth from Bentonville is one con\ntinuous cloud of dust because the\nhighway has not yet been rebuilded.\nThe state department is only main\ntaining it now. A survey made shows\ntnat through Big Three MHe creek\nvalley a complete new route will be\nmade. TrafHc from Bentonville will!\nmove over a new highway with a\nrailroad grade and few abruptions,\ncarrying greater trafHc than the two\nocean river route.\nin Aberdeen tms tramc wtn oe\nfloated without hinderance to the\nbridge approach. On third street\nZane Trace intersects with the At\nlantic Pacific highway.\nThe Atlantic-Pacific through Aber\ndeen is re-located. More than half\nmile to the east, or up the river, the\nroute drops from the river hillside to\nthe river bottom. The relocation\nor rebuilding call for that section to\nbe concrete. After intersecting with\nthe bridge approach from the east it\nveers northward striking Third St.\njust north of the Methodist church.\nFollowing that street westward to\nFishing Gut creek a new concrete\nspan will be built, thus making the\ntrend of that thoroughfare directly\nthrough the town, while the route\nfrom the north fits directly with the\narrangement, making what might be\nsaid the permanent monuments for\nAberdeen for time to come.\nAlready inquiry is made concern\ning Aberdeen as a place to make a\nhome. There is a wonderful river\nbottom area there where residential\nplace is at every hand. Conditions ap\npeal, and it is whispered that there\nis every reason to believe that the\nnew bridge will soon be brought to a\nfree toll bridge.\nCrowds are continually watching\nthe progress of work upon the bridge\npiers at the points where started.\nThese people learn of the great change\nthat the improvement has brought for\nAberdeen. How much this is to be\nis speculative, but the native citizens\nthereabout say \"In five years you\nwon't know us.\"\nTook Wife Ride\nIn Wheelbarrow\nOn Election Bet\nBethel, Ohio.\u2014Mrs. Charles Fagley\nmade her husband pay an election bet\nhe made with her over the outcome of\nthe election which brought toil and\nsweat from him. They reside one\nhalf mile south of Bethel, and there\nis a hill to ascend before one reaches\nBethel. Mr. Fagley got the Republi\ncan inspiration in his system going,\nbut Mrs. Fagley couldn't see like him.\nShe held that the Democrats were\ncoming with a rush. They wagered\nthat whoever won was to get a wheel\nbarrow ride to town, the other fur\nnishing the power. Mrs. Fagley\nwinning had her husband bring the\ncarriage around for her and stepped\nin and not only rode to town, but got\nquite a thrill greeting her friends\nthereabout.\nSchool Consolidation\nCompleted At Ripley\nFinal details of consolidating the\nRipley Village and Union Township\nschools were complete last Friday\nevening, when at a meeting of the\nRipley Board of Education, President\nR. B. Smith and Member Crabb hand\ned in their resignations.\nIn accordance with an arrange\nment made about two months ago\nwhen the consolidation plans ^vere\nlaid, the three remaining members,\nBuchanan, Drake and Ellis then ap\npointed August Fauth to fill the un\nexpired term of Prof. Smith and A.\nR. Hicks to fill the unexpired term\nof Mr. Crabb. Fauth's term will be\nfor three years and that of Hicks will\nbe one year. Both Fauth and Hicks\nwere members of the Union Township\nBoard of Education and were named\nby President Wiley as the two mem\nbers from the Township to represent\nthe latter on the Board of Educa\ntion of the new district which will be\nknown as the Ripley Village School\nDistrict.\nMr. Buchanan, who was Vice\nPresident <of the Ripley Board of\nEducation automatically becomes\nPresident of the new Board with the\nretirement of Mr. Smith and Mr.\nFauth who was nominated for Vice\nPresident by Member Drake and\nunanimously elected to that place.\nChicken Pic Supper To\nBe Heid At Winchester\nThe Ladies of the Winchester Pres\nbyterian church will serve a Chicken\nPie Supper cafeteria style, at Neu's\nGarage, Saturday, November 22, be\nginning at 4:30 p. m.\nGOITRE REMOVED\nSIX YEARS AGO\nMrs. Peart Bishop, 1018 Madison Ave,\nCotumbus, Ohio\nSays \"I wiit teit or write how 1 pre\nvented an operation with Sorbol-Quad\nrupte a colorless liniment easy to ap\nply and not expensive. My neck was\nreduced 1 inches and never bothered\nsince.\"\nGet more information at W. A.\nBrown's or write Sorbol Company,\nMechanicsburg, Ohio.\nYou Can Buy\n/2tg jBargams Wott?\nCome in and See My\nNew Prices\non\nSuits and Overcoats\nWit// 5at?e You Money\nSAM R. FREE,\nHiLLSBORO, OHIO\nNEW CHEVROLET\nS!X ON MSPLAY\n1931 Models Show Many\nImprovements At New\nLow Prices.\nChevrolet's new car for 1931, priced\nsubstantially below current levels,\nwent on display Saturday through\nout the nation.\nHeralded as \"The Great American\nValue,\" the new car boasts a two\ninch increase in wheelbase, larger and\nroomier bodies by Fisher with mohair\nor broadcloth as optional trimming,\nand scores of refinements in appear\nance and performance despite the\nnew prices which bring the level for\nthe 1931 car to a far lower figure\nthan any Chevrolet, four or six, has\never sold.\nDealers through the United States\nput the new models on exhibition\nSaturday morning for the first time,\nnearly two months in advance of the\ncustomary date for the showing of\nthe annual new car. This move in\nadvancing the announcement date, it\nwas felt by Chevrolet officials, would\nrender a distinct contribution to the\ncause of general business revival\nby insuring extraordinary activity\nduring two normally dull business\nmonths for the 200,000 people through\nout the United States who depend di\nrectly upon Chevrolet for their liveli\nhood.\nThe nineteen domestic production\nplants of the Chevrolet organization\nare now in full swing on the new\nmodel, and shipments are going out\nto dealers to assure immediate de\nlivery of all models.\nFundamentally the new mode! em\nbodies the same basic features which\nsince the introduction of the Chevrolet\nSix, enabled it to achieve a popularity\nexceeding Chevrolet's former four cyl\ninder model and four times as great\nas any other six cylinder car. How\never, scores of improvements and re\nfinements have been made this year\u2014\nevery change designed to increase the\nsmartness, performance, safety and\ndurability of this latest General\nMotors model.\nAmong the improvements are a\nfully insulated front compartment,\neasier steering, more durable clutch,\nsmoother and quieter transmission,\nand liberal use of rustless chromium\nplate on exposed bright parts. Four\nLovejoy hydraulic shock absorbers,\nand fully enclosed, weatherproof 4\nwheel brakes continue as standard\nequipment.\nIn the line of nine body types are\nthree open models\u2014the roadster,\nphaeton and sport roadster, and six\nclosed models\u2014the coach, sedan, spe\ncial sedan, the three-window coupe,\nthe five window coupe, and the sport\ncoupe.\nAll sport models come equipped\nwith the new and popular chrome\nplated radiator grille. All models\nhave smart new wire wheels, with\n4.75 by 19 tires, as standard equip\nment. Hubs are very large, of the\nconcealed bolt type, with hub caps\nof gleaming chromium plate set off\nby a black ring circling the Chevrolet\nemblem in the center. Wheel finishes\nharmonize with the wide variety of\nbody combinations.\nThreatening Letters\nCaused Man To Be\nSent To Sanitarium\nGeorgetown, Ohio.\u2014Upon charges\nentered by two federal secret service\nrepresentatives, B. F. Calvin was\nbrought before Judge Quinian of the\nProbate Court for commitment. The\nofficers had taken Calvin into custody\nat Russellville, after it'was estabiish\ned that he had sent theatening letters\nthrough the mail. One had gone to\nAndrew Mellon, United States Treas\nurer, ordering $100,000 deposited in a\nCincinnati bank. It was said that\nCalvin called at thet bank to as\ncertain whether the money had arriv\ned, and later wrote to W. O. Woods,\nassistant treasurer, giving notice that\nif the money was not forthcoming\nthat he intended blowing their lights\nout. When Calvin was questioned in\ncourt, he admitted sending the let\nters, that he had been spiritually in\nspired, and that he needed money for\ncharitable work among the needy\nabout Russellville. Commitment was\nmade to Longview hospital.\nGen. Grant's Portfoiio\nIs Added To Collection\nGeorgetown, Ohio.\u2014Two more items\nfrom the personal efFects of General\nUlysses S. Grant were received last\nweek and added to the large list to be\nseen at the little brick school house\non Dutch Hill, where he attended\nschool as a boy. These came from\nGeneral Ulysses S. Grant, III at\nWashington, D. C., who takes so\nmuch interest in th^ little school\nhouse which Georgetown peopie\ncherish and see daily growing into\ngenera! attention.\nThese were a portfolio and pad of\nmonogramed letter writing paper.\nThe portfolio is of purple color, while\nthe writing paper shows that age has\ndimmed the ruling thereon until it is\njust visible.\nVisitors continue to increase to the\nlittle school building, one being reg\nistered from Hong Kong, China, last\nweek.\n-TIME TO THHWK OF CHR!STMAS!E\nSECOMD COLDEM ARROW\nJUBKEE WEEK\nNOVEMBER IS TO^NOVEMBER M, HNCLUSHVE\nJubilee Week ends Saturday Night! Just three days more to save in this\ndramatic demonst ration of 558 store Buying Power Value Giving. Come!\nJUBILEE WEEK ONLY!\nWARD'S CUT PRICES!\nTraii Biazer Tires\n7ypico/ ^ooingg ListeJ\u2014otAer 5izes ot proportionate savings\nSize 29x4.40\nReg. Price, $4.79\nJubiiee Price\nSize 29x4.50\nReg. Price, $5.30\nJubilee Price\nSize 30x3%\nReg. Price, $4.29\nJubilee Price\nSize 30x4.50\nReg. Price, $5.38\nJubilee Price\n$3 83 $4 84 $3 43 $4 30\nJust Think of it\nSavings oS /Q\n8 Piece Dining\nRoom Suite\n$10.00 ig*iQt